# Generation 296 (deep-reasoning M0, comprehension frame 1): a leading DETERMINER on
# the subject of a class statement — the way Wikipedia lead sentences and ordinary
# prose phrase a membership fact. First step of prose->fact extraction
# (docs/plans/deep-reasoning.md §4): the SAME comprehension parser that stores a
# user's "X is a Y" now also digests "A whale is a mammal". Hermetic base, so every
# fact here is genuinely learned, not recalled.

# Leading article on the subject, as an assertion.
> A whale is a mammal
< Learned: mammal(whale).
# ...and queried back with the article too (verb-first).
> is a whale a mammal?
< Yes.
# "The" + "an" variants.
> The dog is an animal
< Learned: animal(dog).
> is the dog an animal?
< Yes.
# The payoff for deep reasoning: an extracted membership feeds a MULTI-HOP category
# chain (whale -> mammal -> vertebrate) over a universal rule.
> every mammal is a vertebrate
< Learned rule: vertebrate(X) :- mammal(X).
> is a whale a vertebrate?
< Yes.
# Regression: a bare subject (no article) still stores the membership as before.
> zorb is a blit
< Learned: blit(zorb).

# gen298 (frame 2): PAST-TENSE copula "was/were", as Wikipedia phrases historical
# subjects. Tenseless membership fact; combines with the leading article of frame 1.
> Socrates was a philosopher
< Learned: philosopher(socrates).
> is socrates a philosopher?
< Yes.
> A dinosaur was an animal
< Learned: animal(dinosaur).
> is a dinosaur an animal?
< Yes.
# The NOUN "era" is not mistaken for a copula (no article follows), so this stays
# an honest wall rather than a misparse.
> the victorian era was long
< I don't understand that yet.

# gen299 (frame 3): MULTI-WORD subject and class join into one atom.
> The blue whale is a marine mammal
< Learned: marine_mammal(blue_whale).
# gen299 (frame 4): a trailing PREPOSITIONAL PHRASE yields TWO facts from one
# sentence — the class AND a located_in edge (the seed of geographic multi-hop).
> France is a country in Europe
< Learned: country(france), located_in(france, europe).
# gen299 (frame 6): locative frames — "is located in", bare "is in", "is part of".
> France is located in Europe
< Learned: located_in(france, europe).
> Sicily is part of Italy
< Learned: part_of(sicily, italy).
# A predicate adjective (no article) is NOT a membership: honest wall, not long(x).
> the sky is blue
< I don't understand that yet.
